    "promptZh": "There are three judges in a court, who have the following probabilities of reaching the correct verdict: Judge 1 Judge 2 Judge 3 p p 1/2 A verdict is only decided if at least two of the judges agree. What is the probability of the court reaching the correct verdict?",
    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "The court reaches the correct verdict if either two or three judges are correct. The obvious solution of 1 −P(All three wrong) ignores the scenario in which one judge is correct and the other two are wrong. You have to write out all the possible combinations: P(Three correct) = pp(1/2) P(Two correct) = pp(1 −1/2) + p(1 −p)(1/2) + (1 −p)p(1/2) = p2 −(1/2)p2 + p −p2 = p −(1/2)p2 P(Correct verdict reached) = P(Two or three correct) = (1/2)p2 + p −(1/2)p2 = p. Note that you cannot use the binomial coeﬃcients, 3 \u0001 and 3 \u0001 , as the judges don't all have the same p.",
