    "answer": "",
    "explanation": "This is question 6.6 from Joshi et al. (2008). It is similar to the previous question as it also requires a rewrite trick followed by some calculus. There is no intuitive solution. If you evaluate eπ and πe numerically, one of them is 22.46 and the other one is 23.14. This makes it a beautiful question, but the beauty can quickly evaporate if your first encounter is during an interview. Now for the trick: you have two expressions, eπ πe and you can take the natural logarithm of both without aﬀecting their relative order: log(eπ) log(πe). You can also divide both expressions by πe without influencing their order, since πe is positive, log(eπ) eπ = π log(e) eπ = log(e) e log(πe) eπ = e log(π) eπ = log(π) π .\n\nNow you've changed the original question into one about the behaviour of the function log(x) x (7) in the region near e and π. Specifically, you want to know whether (7) is increasing or decreasing over this region. So you take its derivative, using the product rule d dx log x x = log x d dx x + 1 x d dx log x = −log x 1 x2 + 1 x2 = 1 x2 (1 −log x) . Now you can evaluate the nature of the function at the two points. At e you have e2 (1 −log e) = 0 and at π you have π2 (1 −log π) . Here, the sign will only depend on the sign of (1 −log π). You know that π is slightly larger than e (π ≈3.14 and e ≈2.71) so you can write (1 −log π) = (1 −log e1+k) (8) where k is some small positive quantity. Then (1 −log π) = (1 −(1 + k)) = −k which is negative. Writing it with the k as in (8) actually helps to solve the problem. At e, the derivative is 0, so you know it has a critical point there. For all the values thereafter, k will be increasing so the derivative will be negative, implying the function f(x) = log(x)/x is decreasing after e. Below is a plot of the function with the important points highlighted. e π −0.1 0.1 0.2 0.3 x log(x) x That means log(e) e > log(π) π eπ > πe\n\nand a calculator confirms this, eπ = 23.14 πe = 22.46.",
